The <b>Rock Wren</b> (<i>Salpinctes obsoletus</i>) is a small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Songbird" title="Songbird">songbird</a> of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wren" title="Wren">wren</a> family. It is the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotypic_taxon" title="Monotypic taxon">only species</a> in the genus <i>Salpinctes</i>.
The 12&nbsp;cm long adults have grey-brown upperparts with small black and white spots and pale grey underparts with a light brown rump. They have a light grey line over the eye, a long slightly decurved thin <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beak" title="Beak">bill</a>, a long barred tail and dark legs.
Their breeding habitat is dry rocky locations, including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canyon" title="Canyon">canyons</a>, from southwestern <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a> south to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Costa_Rica" title="Costa Rica">Costa Rica</a>. This <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> builds a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_nest#Cup" title="Bird nest">cup nest</a> in a crevice or cavity, usually among rocks.
These birds are permanent residents in the south of their range, but northern populations <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_migration" title="Bird migration">migrate</a> to warmer areas from the central <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and southwest <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a> southwards. They are occasional vagrants in the eastern United States.
These birds actively hunt on the ground, around and under objects, probing with their bill as their extraction tool. They mainly eat <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insect" title="Insect">insects</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider" title="Spider">spiders</a>.
This bird's song is a trill, becoming more varied during the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nesting_season" title="Nesting season">nesting season</a>.
